Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Cardio Dataset¶

Marcos Barragán Corredera¶

30/10/2020¶

In this practice I am going to produce an exploratory data analysis (EDA) of cardiac diseases dataset, trying to find NA values, duplicated entries, and relations between variables and target: Cardio Disease.

This dataset contains 70000 entries divided in 13 variables.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Familiarizing with the data¶

First of all, we have to load the csv dataset.

In [3]:
cardio = pd.read_csv("cardio_train.csv", delimiter = ';')

If we check what kind of data we are trating, we will see the variables I have named and defined at the beggining of the work.

As I said, these dataset contains 70k entries divided in 13 columns. These features are: These features are:

  • age: Age of people in the dataset | int (days)

  • height: Height of people | int (cm)

  • weight: People´s Weight | float (kg)

  • gender: 1: Female, 2: Male | int (binary)

  • a_pi: Systolic blood pressure | int (mmHg)

  • ap_lo: Diastolic blood pressure | int (mmHg)

  • cholesterol: Cholesterol Level | 1: normal, 2: above normal, 3: well above normal | int (binary)

  • gluc: Glucose Level in blood | 1: normal, 2: above normal, 3: well above normal | int (binary)

  • smoke: Smoking habits | 0: Non-Smoker, 1: Smoker | int (binary)

  • alco: Alcoholic habits | 0: Non Alcoholic, 1: Alcoholic | int (binary)

  • active: Physical activity | 0: Active, 1: Non Active | int (binary)

  • cardio: Presence or absence of cardiovascular disease, target Variable | 0: Non Cardio Disease, 1: Cardio Disease | int (binary)

We see that there is a variable called id, which corresponds to the index of the entries. This is completly unusefull, because Python puts an index itself, so we don´t need two entries for indexes.

Because of this, I will drop idcolumn.

In [5]:
cardio = cardio.drop('id', axis=1)

Secondly, we have to transform some variables:

  • age data must be converted into years.

  • weight and heightare not so usefull as they would be if we link them by creating a new variable called: IMC (Spanish accronyms for Corporal Mass Index). We can create it by implementing the relation: $$IMC = \frac{weight}{height^2}$$, where weight must be in kg and height in cm.

  • ap_lo and ap_hi should be converted into a single variable. I will call it BP (Blood Pressure), and it will take the values:

    • Low Pressure: Systolic pression under 80 and Diastolic pression < 60.
    • Normal pressure: Systolic pression up to 120 and Diastolic pression < 80.
    • Elevated pressure: Systolic <= 140 and Diastolic < 90.
    • High Pressure level 1: Systolic between 140-160 and/or Diastolic between 91-99.
    • High Pressure level 2: Systolic between 160-179 and/or Diastolic between 100-109.
    • High Pressure level 3: Systolic higher than 180 and/or Diastolic higher than 110.
In [6]:
cardio['age'] = cardio.age.map(lambda x: round(x/365)) 

cardio['IMC'] = cardio.weight/(cardio.height/100)**2

cardio['IMC'] = cardio.IMC.map(lambda x: 'Underweight' if (x < 18.5) else 'Normal' if (18.5 < x < 25) else 
                       'Overweight' if (25 <= x <30) else 'Obese')
In [7]:
def BP(datos):
    
    if (datos['ap_hi'] <= 90) | (datos['ap_lo'] <= 60):
        
        return 'Low Blood Pressure'
    
    if (datos['ap_hi'] <= 120) and (datos['ap_lo'] <= 80):
        
        return 'Normal'
    
    if (datos['ap_hi'] >= 120 and datos['ap_hi'] < 140) | (datos['ap_lo']>80 and datos['ap_lo'] < 90):
    
        return 'Elevated'
    
    if (datos['ap_hi'] >= 140 and datos['ap_hi'] < 160) | (datos['ap_lo'] >= 90 and datos['ap_lo'] < 100):
   
        return 'High Pressure Level 1'
    
    if (datos['ap_hi'] >= 160 and datos['ap_hi'] < 180) | (datos['ap_lo'] >= 100 and datos['ap_lo'] < 110):
        
        return 'High Pressure Level 2'
    
    if (datos['ap_hi'] >= 180) | (datos['ap_lo'] >= 110):
        
        return 'High Pressure Level 3'

cardio['BP'] = cardio.apply(BP, axis=1)

We can implement a scatter plot between non-binary values to check the outliers and error values:

In [246]:
#Creating a new dataframe which only contains non-binary variables of the dataset. 

pp = pd.DataFrame({"Age": cardio.age, 
                   "Weight": cardio.weight, 
                   "Height": cardio.height,
                   "ap_hi": cardio.ap_hi,
                   "ap_lo": cardio.ap_lo, 
                   "IMC":cardio.IMC, 
                   "BP": cardio.BP})

sns.pairplot(pp);

As we can see, there are some mistakes in the features. We can notice it in:

  • height have a minimum value of 55 cm and a maximum value of 250 cm, which are exorbitant values for this variable.
  • weight have a minimum value of 10 kg, which is ridiculous, and a maximum of 200 kg (which is strange but not impossible).
  • ap_lo and ap_hi have negative minimum values, which is impossible, but also maximum values bigger than 10000, which must be a mistake. If we look at the pairplot, we will see many outliers that we should remove.

Then, in order to get a better EDA fro the data, I should drop out this values. Particularly, I will delete:

  • Height values over 200 cm and under 140 cm.
  • Weight values under 40 kg.
  • Systolic BP under 70 mmHg and over 230 mmHg
  • Diastolic BP under 40 mmHg and over 170 mmHg
  • Of course rows where ap_hi - ap_lo < 0 must be thrown away too.

EDA analysis of the corrected dataset¶

Once I have transformed and improved the cardio dataset, I will try to get the relations between variables with each other and with target column cardio.

Because of many variables of this dataset are binary or discrete variables, it is not really usefull to trace histograms or scatter plots of them. In order to achieve the best results, I will relate them with the target values using crosstabs, count plots or boxplots involving those binary variables. That is the reason why there will appear so many plotsin this study.

a) Age as a factor of cardiac Diseaseas¶

First, I would like to have a look on the ages distribution for cardio diseases.

The distribution of BMI for each gender is clear: there are many more females with higher BMI than males (this could be related to the big differences between number of females and males in the dataset).

We can also see that most of the people in the set is overweighted, and there is so little amount of people underweighted.

In that boxplot, we see that above normal values follow the same trend: BP problems appear a bit earlier for males (we see it at the first quartile), but they seem to have the same median value for both gender (except elevated one, whose median is slightly lower for males, indicating that men develop elevated BP problems earlier than women).

We can see in that plots that there is not much information to get; this may be because there are only two possible values for each variables: 0 or 1. We don't know what criterion people have followed to complete this values: what do they consider for smoking, or what do they consider to be alcoholic or active, etc. If there were more than two values to choose (I mean, for example: 0-0.33: Non alcoholic, 0.33-0.66: Occasionally alcoholic consumer, 0.66-1: habitual alcoholic, it will be better, because we would be able to relate better those variables and target cardio).

Anyway, we can also see that activity lead to reduce chances of CV disease (as we expected).

Correlations between data¶

If we perform a correlation plot between variables, once we have corrected and improved the dataframe, we will be able to see how related they are between each other.

In [244]:
ax, figure = plt.subplots(1, figsize = (18,12))

corr = cardio2.corr()

#triu numpy's command return the upper triangular matrix of a matrix given. I put +1 because I want to show the main diagonal 
#values of correlation matrix on the plot. 

mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=bool), +1) 



ax = sns.heatmap(
    corr, 
    vmin=-1, vmax=1, center=0,
    cmap= 'coolwarm',
    square=True,
    mask = mask
)
ax.set_xticklabels(
    ax.get_xticklabels(),
#     ax.xticks(np.arange(12), ('Age','Gender', 'Height', 'Weight'), rotation = 45)
    rotation=45,
    horizontalalignment='right'
);

We can see that target variable cardio is positively correlated to ap_hi, ap_lo, cholesterol, gluc, age and weight, as we have seen in the plots that I have made before.

We can also check again that smoke and alco don't seem to have relations whith cardio.

One important thing is that active and cardio have negative correlation (slightly but present): this is because the more active you are, the less chances of getting CVD you have.

Other important relations appear between: ap_lo and ap_hi(obviously), cholesterol and gluc, height and gender and smoke and alco.

Conclusion¶

Once I have performed the EDA for this dataset of CV diseases, there are some conclusions that seem important:

  • Age is a risk factor for developing a CVD.
  • IMC is a very high risk factor for CVD as it becomes higher.
  • cholesterol is a very high risk factor in the development of CV problems.
  • BP tends to contribute to get CV problems.
  • gluc level seems to be an important factor in CVD development.

On the other hand:

  • smoke and alco in the way they are presented are not usefull for this study.
  • active values are a little bit usefull, but they should be redimensioned in order to return better results to our study.
